questiontext.text:
A table of integrals

We could use a table of derivatives to find integrals, but the more common ones are usually found in a ‘Table of Integrals’ such as that shown below. You could check the entries in this table using your knowledge of differentiation. Try this for yourself.

Table 1: Integrals of Common Functions

\(f(x)\) \[\int\,f(x)\,\mathrm{d}x\]
constant \( k\) \(kx+c\)
\(x\) \(\dfrac{1}{2}x^2+c\)
\(x^2\) \(\dfrac{1}{3}x^3+c\)
\(x^n,\,n\neq-1\) \(\dfrac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+c\),  \(n\ne-1\)
\(x^{-1}\) \(\left(\text{or }\dfrac{1}{x}\right)\) \(\ln|x|+c\)
\(\cos(x)\) \(\sin(x)+c\)
\(\sin(x)\) \(-\cos(x)+c\)
\(\cos(kx)\) \(\dfrac{1}{k}\sin(kx)+c\)
\(\sin(kx)\) \(-\dfrac{1}{k}\cos(kx)+c\)
\(\tan(kx)\) \(\dfrac{1}{k}\ln|\sec(kx)|+c\)
\(e^x\) \(e^x+c\)
\(e^{-x}\) \(-e^{-x}+c\)
\(e^{kx},\,k\neq0\) \(\dfrac{1}{k}e^{kx}+c\)

When dealing with the trigonometric functions the variable \(x\) must always be measured in radians and not degrees. Note that the fourth entry in the Table, for \(x^n\), is not valid for \(n=-1\) but is valid for any other value \(n\), positive or negative, whole number or fractional. When \(n=-1\) use the fifth entry in the Table.

Example

Use Table 1 to find the indefinite integral of \(x^7\): that is, find \[\int{x^7}\ \mathrm{d}x\]

Solution

From Table 1 note that \[\int{x^n}\ \mathrm{d}x = \dfrac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+c\]

In words, this states that to integrate a power of \(x\), increase the power by 1, and then divide the result by the new power. With n = 7 we find \[\int{x^7}\ \mathrm{d}x = \dfrac{x^{8}}{8}+c\]

Example

Find the indefinite integral of \(\cos (5x)\): that is, find \[\int \cos (5x)\ \mathrm{d}x\]

Solution

From Table 1 note that \[\int{\cos(kx)}\ \mathrm{d}x = \dfrac{1}{k}\sin(kx)+c\]

With \(k=5\) we find \[\int{\cos(5x)}\ \mathrm{d}x = \dfrac{1}{5}\sin(5x)+c\]

Example

Find \[\int \cos (5t)\ \mathrm{d}t\]

Solution

We integrated \(\cos(5x)\) in the previous example. Now the independent variable is \(t\), so simply use Table 1 and replace every \(x\) with a \(t\). With \(k = 5\) we find \[\int{\cos(5t)}\ \mathrm{d}x = \dfrac{1}{5}\sin(5t)+c\]

It follows immediately that, for example,

\[\int{\cos(5\omega)}\ \mathrm{d}\omega = \dfrac{1}{5}\sin(5\omega)+c,\] \[\int{\cos(5u)}\ \mathrm{d}u = \dfrac{1}{5}\sin(5u)+c\]

Example

Find the indefinite integral of \(\dfrac{1}{x}\): that is, find \[\int \dfrac{1}{x}\ \mathrm{d}x\]

Solution

This integral deserves special mention. You may be tempted to try to write the integrand as \(x^{-1}\) and use the fourth row of Table 1. However the formula \[\int{x^{n}}\ \mathrm{d}x = \dfrac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+c\] is not valid when \(n = -1\) as Table 1 makes clear. This is because we can never divide by zero. Look to the fifth entry of the table and you will see \[\int{x^{-1}}\ \mathrm{d}x = \ln|x|+c.\]

Example

Find \[\int 12\,\mathrm{d}x\] and \[\int 12\,\mathrm{d}t.\]

Solution

In this example we are integrating a constant, \(12\). Using Table 1 we find

\[\int 12\,\mathrm{d}x = 12x+c\] and \[\int 12\,\mathrm{d}t=12t+c.\]
